@@eThe Arroyo: Desert Jurisdiction Assessment@@N

@@yBureau of Eastern Routes, Comparative Legal Division@@N
@@dFiled under: Layered Jurisdiction, Unpaid Names, Bureaucratic Archaeology@@N

The Arroyo is foreign territory, but its legal architecture is
@@ylegible to us@@N. A dry canyon where water volume was translated into
legal obligation, debts written against drought, oaths notarized
against thirst. Our Division reads its inscriptions the way archivists
read palimpsest parchment -- one regime atop another, none erased.

Five active layers map to familiar categories. @@yKeeper-era
measurement@@N corresponds to our @@dFirst Stone Accord@@N. @@ySalt Ledger
extraction@@N corresponds to our @@dAsh-and-Iron Decades@@N. @@dPyramid
jurisdiction@@N layered Moon-descending language atop earlier systems --
the kind of accumulation our Violet Compact produced when occult
oversight was written over commercial law.

The @@rSynod coercion@@N layer -- "authorized thirst" as prayer and
threat -- has one Midgaard parallel the Reckoning faction will not
stop citing: when our Tithe administrators charged fees for access
to names of the dead.

The @@d"unpaid names"@@N trouble us most. Those who died in arrears had
rites withheld -- names entered as obligations rather than persons.
Our own @@d"deferred names"@@N in the Sepulchur Pasture follow the same
logic: interment pending claim, pending payment, @@rpending
indefinitely@@N. The Reckoning published a comparative table, column by
column. The parallels are @@runcomfortable@@N. The Continuity faction
objected. The Division notes the Arroyo's clerks likely made the
same distinction.

Four powers contest the canyon. @@rCharter Reclaimers@@N run extortion
checkpoints. @@dDustbound Court-Dead@@N demand declarations. The @@rBrood
of the Resin Matriarch@@N infests warm seep zones. @@eFault
Manifestations@@N align to old survey marks.

The canyon walls are overwritten inscriptions. All factions claim
legitimacy from layers none fully understands. Our Bureau recognizes
this because @@ywe practice it ourselves@@N -- Five Eras carved atop
one another in our own registry halls.

The Arroyo is @@dforeign but legible@@N. That legibility is what makes
it @@rdisturbing@@N -- a system we can read is one we might recognize
as our own, written in sand instead of stone.
